			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Pre-Elemental and Elemental Bards<a name="42552"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 27 04 4:04 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I thought goldark gave a pretty good guide, especially for a bard new to raiding.
<br />

<br />
MT: cha + DS + (grp) resists = primary role
<br />
melee DPS: overhaste + Atk boost = primary role
<br />
caster DPS: DD focus + mana [+ HoS*] = normal combo
<br />
healer: mana + resists [+ HoS*] = normal combo
<br />
[* depending upon line of sight limitations]
<br />

<br />
The number of bards present, along with the simple physical limitation of lag, strongly limits how closely you can follow the 'ideal' twist combinations.
<br />

<br />
Always bear in mind what the key aspect of an encounter is - whether it's burn the mob down asap; a duration MT-healer fight; a control encounter; or something special like a silence effect in operation. Start with the big picture to work down to which cogs in the machine you are best placed to fill.
<br />

<br />
For example, if you are in the MT grp and it's a control fight, playing DS songs is not only useless, it's also potentially causing a wipe. There is no magical 'painting by numbers' guide to raiding. Just understand the emphasis of the raid, and understand the point of your songs, and you won't go far wrong.
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
